			<h4>What is the cause of baldness?</h4>
												<p>It is known that the male hormone, testosterone, gets converted to another male hormone, 5-dihydroxytestosterone (5-DHT), in the hair follicles. Under the influence of 5-DHT hair follicles in the front and the top of the scalp begin to become more fine over the years in genetically susceptible men. Hair growth also gets restricted and eventually the hair disappears completely. There are different stages of baldnes</p>
                                             <hr />
                                             
                                             <h4>Stage 1</h4>
											<p>The first signs of trouble appear when frontal recession begins to appear in the hairline</p>
                                           
                                           <h4>Stage 2</h4>
                                           <p>Recession starts to become noticeable as hairline pushes back even further</p>
                                           
                                           <h4>Stage 3</h4>
                                           <p>With recession, hair gradually begins to thin on the crown. This thinning becomes visible and continues to increase in size rapidly</p>
                                           
                                           <h4>Stage 4</h4>
                                           <p>Male pattern baldness is complete when the crown and frontal region are completely devoid of hair and the horse shoe shape becomes visible.</p>



                                             
